<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow retraces its steps after
initial advance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By  FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Blue chip shares receded yesterday afternoon after an early advance, but
broader indices maintained mild firmness as investors shrugged off the
dollar's continued weakness, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average ended a net 2.59 lower at 3,667.05, but the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was 1.56 ahead at 447.63. Advancing issues on the New
York SE had a three-to-two edge over decliners. In the secondary markets,
the American SE composite was up 0.81 at 423.48 and the Nasdaq composite
added 1.96 at 704.01.
A modest 263m shares were traded on the Big Board, with many investors
inactive in the run-up to the long Independence Day weekend and a keenly
awaited Federal Reserve policy-making session early next week. But there was
extra activity generated by money managers adjusting their books a day ahead
of the final trading session of the second quarter.
For the second day running, the blue chips shifted direction during the
mid-afternoon. At the opening, stocks picked up where they had left off the
previous session. Share prices moved steadily higher, building on Tuesday's
late rally, which had whittled down a 45-point Dow deficit to just 15 points
by the close.
The dollar remained a concern but stocks appeared to have broken step with
its fluctuations. Yesterday the greenback continued to slide against the
Japanese currency, but investors took the news in their stride. Later, when
stocks lost their forward momentum, the flagging currency served as an
obvious scapegoat, but it never was a big factor.
In the fixed-rate markets, traders also seemed resigned to the dollar's
latest stumble, giving equities some breathing room. Bonds inched forward in
spite of an upward revision of the government's estimate of first-quarter
gross domestic product to 3.4 per cent. Economists were expecting no change
in the earlier estimate of 3.0 per cent.
But investors discounted the relevance of the first three months of the year
to the Fed's current thinking. The report was not expected to influence the
outcome of next week's policy session.
If it were not for a fresh setback for strike-bound Caterpillar, the Dow
industrials would have showed a gain. In the event, the issue shed a further
Dollars 2 to Dollars 102 1/8 . International Paper gave back Dollars  3/4 to
Dollars 67.
The banking sector was generally improved as stocks tracked the course
struck by bonds. NationsBank climbed Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 52 1/2 and
First Interstate appreciated Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 76 5/8 . Citicorp added
Dollars  3/4 at Dollars 39 7/8 as Kidder Peabody initiated coverage of the
issue with an 'outperform' rating.
On the Nasdaq, Novell gained Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 17 and led the most
active list with 9.7m shares traded. At least two securities houses -
Wertheim Schroder and UBS - had lifted their ratings on the issue.
Snapple Beverages firmed Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 21 1/8 after the company
told analysts of its success in the fast-growing market for bottled fruit
juices.
Canada
The Toronto market strengthened as investors began to look ahead to the
release of second-quarter earnings results next month.
The TSE 300 composite index finished 31.4 up at 4,028.2 and advances
outpaced declines by 422 to 293 after volume of 57.9m shares valued at
CDollars 637.7m.
Mexico
Mexican shares opened higher, helped by reports that Mr Alfredo Harp Helu,
the kidnapped financier, had been released by his kidnappers, as well as by
gains on Wall Street. The IPC index was up 24.2, or 1.1 per cent, at
2,256.93.
Brazil
Equities in Sao Paulo had gained a further 5.5 per cent in local currency
terms by midsession as domestic investors in particular took positions
before the introduction of the new currency, the real, tomorrow. The Bovespa
index was 1,949 stronger at 37,585.
The financial markets will be closed tomorrow as the changeover in the
currency takes place.
