<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 94 / International Company News: Nasdaq in trial reform of short
sale regulations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The second-biggest US stock market has changed its rules for a trial period
to make companies less vulnerable to so-called 'bear raids', in which a
company's share price is driven down by speculators seeking to make a quick
profit.
The National Association of Securities Dealers, the authority which runs the
Nasdaq stock market, said yesterday it had received approval from the
Securities and Exchange Commission for the rule change.
The reform would in effect prevent dealers from engaging in the sort of
short sales that can force a company's share price into a downward spiral.
A short sale involves a dealer selling shares it does not own in the hope of
buying them later at a lower price.
If several dealers all sell short a company whose shares are already under
pressure, it can lead to a sharp fall in the price.
Under the NASD's new rule, which will be in force for a trial period of 18
months, dealers will not be able to engage in a short sale at a lower price
than the previous bid price quoted on Nasdaq screens.
In effect, this echoes the 'down-tick' rule applied by the New York Stock
Exchange for stocks traded on its market.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
