<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 94 / Dollar hits yen low on Japanese political uncertainty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH and PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The dollar slipped to a post-1945 low of Y98.55 yesterday amid market
uncertainty about the implications of the appointment of a socialist prime
minister in Japan.
Traders were unsure how Mr Tomiichi Murayama, the new Japanese prime
minister, would handle the US-Japan trade talks. Concern was also expressed
about the Social Democratic party's more sympathetic attitude towards North
Korea.
However, European bond and stock markets stood firm in the face of dollar
weakness.
The fall in the dollar came in spite of an earlier fillip from overnight
comments by Mr Lloyd Bentsen, US Treasury secretary, saying the US would not
use the dollar as a tool of trade policy.
In the most forthright defence yet of a strong dollar from a senior
administration official, Mr Bentsen told a New York audience: 'A stronger
dollar is better for our economy and better for the world's economy.'
Analysts said it was important that that message was should be repeated by a
broad range of senior administration officials, but emphasised that it was
only one component of a successful defence of the dollar.
Most agree that the Federal Reserve will also have to raise US short-term
interest rates.
Although the US currency remained weak, trade was not particularly heavy.
Confused market conditions have driven many participants to the sidelines,
and there are few signs of heavy speculation against the dollar.
The dollar closed in London at Y98.765 from Y100.210 on Tuesday. Against the
D-Mark it finished at DM1.5825 from DM1.5849.
In London the September long gilt future, helped by a successful
floating-rate note auction, was nearly  3/4 of a point higher. The FT-SE 100
Index closed 37.3 higher at 2946.3.
In France, the CAC Index rose 10.57 to 1936.33 while in Germany, the DAX
jumped 28.04 to 2046.30. Government bonds made modest gains in both
countries.
