<PROFILE>_AN-EF3D2ADMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940630
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
What on earth is happening to the world of classical music? Ever since it
originated in the Third Programme, the home of classical music on BBC radio,
now called Radio 3, has been regarded as the last redoubt of highbrow taste.
But if you told BBC mandarins that it was mad not to run a popular classical
network, they muttered about turning Bach into aural wallpaper. Then
commercial radio launched Classic FM, which took millions of listeners from
the BBC. Their Evening Concert (8.00) tended to offer the sort of lollipops
that made Radio 3 men wince. But now what do you find? At 7.30 today,
pre-empting the Classic FM concert by half an hour, Radio 3 broadcasts the
BBC Scottish Symphony Orchestra playing Tchaikovsky's Capriccio Italien and
then Rachmaninov's second piano concerto (yes, Brief Encounter) with pianist
Dmitri Alexeev. And the Classic concert? Today it features contemporary
British music including the broadcast premiere of George Lloyd's Symphonic
Mass performed by the Brighton Festival Chorus and the Bournemouth Symphony
Orchestra. Just who is stealing whose clothes?
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
