<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 94 / Times chief aims for rise to 750,000
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Circulation of The Times at 20p could rise to 750,000, double the sales of a
year ago, senior News International executives believe.
Since the second price cut last week, in response to Mr Conrad Black's
decision to cut the price of the weekday Daily Telegraph from 48p to 30p,
The Times has been selling at around the 600,000 mark and close to 620,000
on Satur-day.
'More people are trying the paper and more people are liking it and staying,
so therefore 750,000 is a reasonable target,' said Mr Peter Stothard, editor
of The Times. He emphasised, however, that he had not been set any
particular circulation figure.
'I have had one letter of complaint from a vicar who didn't think it (the
price cut) was right,' said Mr Stothard.
He expects The Times to sell more this Saturday once people realise that
there is now a 40p differential between The Times at 40p and the 80p Daily
Telegraph on Saturdays.
If The Times were to reach the 750,000 figure it would realise an old dream
of Mr Rupert Murdoch, chairman of News Corporation, owner of The Times.
Journalists who were at The Times when Mr Murdoch took over in 1981 remember
him saying on the newsfloor that he wanted to take the paper's circulation
to three quarters of a million.
Other national dailies including The Independent, The Guardian, the Daily
Mail and the Daily Express are estimated to have been affected by the price
wars between The Times and The Daily Telegraph, but not seriously.
Even at a circulation of 600,000 the 20p Times is almost certainly losing a
significant amount of money because 30p was a level where it was starting to
approach breakeven.
The company is believed to be paying around 15p of the 20p cover price to
the news trade - less than the 17.5p estimated by executives at the
Independent.
According to newspaper industry analysts The Times costs about 16p a copy to
produce. At May's circulation figure of 515,000 - which stirred Mr Black
into action - The Times would lose about Pounds 1.2m a month this year, it
is believed. The circulation has already risen beyond that figure and
pressure will mount on advertisers to start paying a higher rate to reflect
the new circulation.
'That will happen (higher advertising revenues) sooner rather than later,'
Mr Stothard forecast yesterday.
</TEXT>
