<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 94 / Lib Dems set out Lit Dem challenge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Liberal Democrats yesterday outlined some of the evidence they will be
bringing before the High Court this week in order to have the result of the
European parliamentary election in Devon and East Plymouth overturned.
The party - which failed to win the seat by 700 votes, after more than
10,000 people backed a candidate calling himself a Literal Democrat - will
today submit an electoral petition calling for the result to be declared
void and the election to be re-run.
Mr Graham Elson, Liberal Democrat general secretary, said that the party's
case had been backed by statements of protest from electors. He said 269
affidavits had been delivered to party offices in Devon, and a further 120
were expected.
The party is bringing the action under the Representation of the People Act
1983.
The petition will name Mr Frank Palmer, the election returning officer, who
accepted the nomination form of the Literal Democrat candidate, Mr Richard
Huggett. It will also name Mr Giles Chichester, the successful Tory
candidate, so that he can present his case.
</TEXT>
