<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 94 / Management controls criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Councils, health authorities and the National Health Service are spending
more than Pounds 120m a year on management consultants - but they are not
making adequate efforts to track expenditure or assess value for money, the
Audit Commission says today.
The public expenditure watchdog says a study of more than 200 projects found
that up to 60 per cent of consultants' recommendations were ignored; most
projects lacked incentives to complete the job successfully; a third of
projects were commissioned without drawing up any written agreement; and
most assignments in health provision were not put out to tender and had
inadequate briefs.
The commission's report echoes most of the criticisms made in a recently
leaked Cabinet Office Efficiency Unit report on consultants in the civil
service. This found that Whitehall departments and agencies could find
savings of only about Pounds 10m a year from expenditure on consultancy
running at more than Pounds 500m a year.
The Audit Commission says consultants can contribute much to change in the
public sector, especially by providing skills not available in-house. Many
of the reforms in health provision and local government could not have been
implemented so fast without their help, the report says.
However, building up in-house skills might be a cheaper solution in some
cases, the commission believes. There is also concern over the amount of
consultancy used and some of the fees being charged. The report says the
process of buying consultancy is badly managed and could be made much more
effective without adding greatly to the bureaucracy.
There was confusion over how projects should be put out to tender,
weaknesses in specifying the task, a failure to identify all the costs at
the outset, and poor management of the work, especially in monitoring
results.
Local authorities emerged from the study as better than the NHS and health
authorities in many aspects of commissioning consultancy work. Their
performance in choosing consultants and drawing up briefs reflected the
experience of compulsory competitive tendering for local government
services.
Health authorities were better at structuring projects to achieve and
evaluate results. But 70 per cent of health projects were assigned without
competition, the commission found.
The Management Consultancies Association reacted to the report by offering
training in how to get the best out of consultancy.
'When consultancy is purchased with knowledge and at the right level, a 95
per cent satisfaction level is achieved,' said Mr Brian O'Rorke, the
association's director.
Reaching the Peak? Getting Value for Money from Management Consultants.
HMSO. Pounds 6.
</TEXT>
<XX>
