<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 94 / Printing industry recovery 'erratic'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Most of Britain's printing industry accepts that there is an economic
recovery but is disappointed that it has not been stronger, says the latest
survey from the British Printing Industries Federation.
The majority of companies accept that 'the general state of trade is easier
than three months ago', according to the survey. They believe 'conditions
will improve or remain at least as favourable during the months to
September'.
However, the survey found that 'few regard the market as wholly
satisfactory, let alone buoyant, and some consider the general situation has
deteriorated'. It adds: 'The industry had hoped for more.'
The survey points to 'the erratic nature of the recovery'. It is also
worried about the rising cost of printing papers and about price increases
for board and plastic films used by printers.
The survey says that a significant number of larger companies have been
forced to cut their prices because of intensive competition while exporters
are finding it difficult to hold their position though they are maintaining
their markets.
Only half the smaller companies and a quarter of larger ones had been able
to pass on recent price rises for materials and labour.
Only 52 per cent had spare capacity but 30 per cent said their order books
were better than normal for the time of year while a further 57 per cent
said they were normal.
But the survey said that margins had been protected by a higher volume of
work and improvements in productivity helped by the job flexibility clauses
in this year's national industry agreement.
Most companies were confident that they could negotiate flexible working
arrangements with employees to offset this year's national basic pay
increases of about 3 per cent.
</TEXT>
<XX>
