<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 94 / Fidelity drops exit charges on Peps
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fidelity Investments, one of the top five providers of personal equity
plans, is to abolish withdrawal charges on its tax-free Pep unit trusts from
Monday.
It will instead raise the initial charge from 2 per cent to 3 per cent from
August 1, barely two years after introducing the new combined charging
structure into the UK. Annual charges will continue to be levied by the
underlying fund. Ms Mary Blair, executive director for product development,
said market research had shown that investors found withdrawal charges
confusing.
In June 1992, Fidelity cut the initial charge on all its unit trust Peps
from 5.25 per cent to 2 per cent and introduced tapering exit charges over
three years. Other fund management groups followed.
In May, Gartmore said it would abandon withdrawal charges on its unit trust
Peps because of investor confusion over the charges and increase the initial
charge from 2 per cent to 3 per cent.
However, Gartmore and Fidelity said that the level of early redemptions on
the Peps has been very low, while Ms Blair said that the difference between
an initial charge of 2 per cent and 3 per cent was not great in investors'
eyes.
