<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 94 / Treasury and MoD in row over cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Senior officials at the Ministry of Defence and the Treasury have failed to
finalise plans for cuts in military expenditure following a row over the way
in which compensation will be paid to service personnel who become
redundant, James Blitz writes.
Just two weeks before the announcement of large cuts in Britain's defence
programme, Treasury officials are insisting that redundancy payments for the
25,000 servicemen and women who will lose their jobs should come from the
MoD budget.
However, defence officials are refusing to bow to the Treasury's demand,
fearing that the payment of redundancy money would further deplete their
budget in future years. Total redundancy payments following next month's
review - called Front Line First - could total many millions of pounds.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the defence secretary, has already had to find cuts of
Pounds 750m in the current financial year to meet the expenditure targets
set out in the last Budget. However it is understood that the Defence Cost
Studies programme, which is examining ways of reducing military support
services, has cut spending by much more than this.
Treasury officials, who are in the early stages of another tough public
spending round, argue that the excess savings are not for the defence
department to keep.
</TEXT>
