attacked the party's candidate over the crucial issue of Monklands District
Council, then made a hasty retraction.
The row broke just as Labour for the first time said it was poised to hold
the seat in the face of a strong challenge from the Scottish National party.
It is defending a majority of nearly 16,000.
Yesterday the Glasgow Evening Times published an article by Mr Jimmy Wray,
MP for Glasgow Provan, in which he challenged Mrs Helen Liddell, the Labour
candidate, over her statement last week that Airdrie, the centre of
Monklands East, was discriminated against in allocations of capital spending
by Monklands council compared with neighbouring Coatbridge.
However two-and-half hours after the article appeared Mr Wray issued a
statement saying he had now examined the figures for council spending in
Airdrie and Coatbridge used by Mrs Liddell and said she was right.
Mr Alex Salmond, the Scottish National party leader, said the entire Labour
line on the Monklands council issue was a fraud.
