<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 94 / Mexican financier released
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The kidnapped Mexican financier Mr Alfredo Harp Helu was released on Tuesday
night, after his family had agreed to pay a ransom which his abductors said
was less than Dollars 30m.
Mr Harp, president of Banamex-Acival, Mexico's largest financial
institution, and one of the country's wealthiest men, was kidnapped on March
14 near his house in the south of Mexico City. His abduction sent Mexico's
stock market tumbling.
He is pictured right, in an AP photo, during his captivity and holding a
copy of a Mexican newspaper, dated June 19.
Several hundred rich Mexican businessmen have been kidnapped in recent
years, mostly in the provinces, but none was as prominent as Mr Harp.
In April, Mr Angel Losada, a wealthy retailer whose family controls Grupo
Gigante, was kidnapped in Mexico City, and it is believed that he is still
being held captive.
The families of kidnap victims generally do not co-operate with the police,
whom many suspect of being involved with the kidnapping gangs. In an effort
to combat organised crime, the Mexican government set up a new national
security agency in April, the day after Mr Losada was seized.
</TEXT>
