<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 94 / World Cup '94: Fairytale for Saudis as Belgium falter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Presumably it is all to be found somewhere in A Thousand and One Nights. But
Saudi Arabia, a team which by its own reckoning pulled off a minor miracle
merely in qualifying for the World Cup, performed an even greater one here
one yesterday by beating Belgium 1-0 and thus moving on to the next round
against Sweden.
The Saudi victory was no fluke. It was won by virtue of stout defence, fine
goalkeeping and the sort of goal that comes strictly from the realms of
fantasy.
In the fifth minute, Owairan moved forward from the centre circle. Before
him were deployed the Belgian back four and Michel Preud'homme in goal,
previously impregnable in the tournament. You could have got long odds
against him even reaching the penalty area.
In the sort of dribble that combined much skill and balance, plus a couple
of lucky bounces, he took on all four one at a time and left them for dead.
The coup de grace was perfect, a delicate chip over the head of the
advancing Preud'homme.
And then his teammates made it hold up, unlike last week when a similar
early lead against Holland was lost. The heads and legs of the back four -
Al-Jawad, Al-Khlaiwi, Zebermawi and, above all, Madani - frustrated attack
after attack.
Even so, a more imaginative team than plodding Belgium, with so much
possession, should surely have at least made it even. But Enzo Scifo, the
alleged mastermind, seemed to be under the impression that all his forwards
were eight feet tall, so often did he punt it high into the Saudi goalmouth.
Sure, chances were missed. Josip Weber, a half-time substitute, was the
prime culpit, high on two close headers and a volley all in the last 15
minutes. But Al-Deayea, now surely to be ranked alongside Preud'homme as the
best goalkeeper in the Cup, was not forced into a serious save after the
64th minute when he twisted to clutch a deflected shot from Philippe Albert.
When it was done, the paper confetti showered down from the upper seats and
thin Arabian horns punctuated the din. And here's the interesting thing;
Saudi Arabia did it without their best player, Fuad Amin, suspended after
picking up two earlier yellow cards.
</TEXT>
<XX>
