<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 94 / UK ready to accept alternative candidate for EU job
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The British government sought to draw a line under the row over the
presidency of the European Commission by suggesting yesterday that it was
ready to accept one of several new candidates who have emerged for the post.
Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, said that 'five or six' new names
were being discussed by European Union governments as alternatives to Mr
Jean-Luc Dehaene, the Belgian prime minister.
Mr Dehaene's candidacy was vetoed by Mr John Major, prime minister, at last
weekend's Corfu summit. But Mr Hurd, speaking on the eve of the German
presidency of the EU, said the new candidates were all 'broadly acceptable'
to the London government.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, took the same position by stressing that
Britain's decision to veto Mr Dehaene's appointment did not foreshadow a
decisive shift in Britain's commitment to the EU.
Mr Clarke emphasised his personal support for the eventual goal of economic
and monetary union and said the government was prepared to see a successor
to Mr Jacques Delors committed to deepening as well as widening the European
Union.
But his comments in a speech at the Konrad Adenauer foundation in Bonn
enraged Conservative party Euro-sceptics, who accused him of undermining a
reassertion at the Corfu summit by Mr John Major of Britain's national
sovereignty.
The speech also failed to persuade many in his Christian Democrat audience
that the London government's pledge to remain 'at the heart of Europe' would
be matched by a constructive approach in practice.
Mr Klaus Kinkel, the German foreign minister, set out a modest programme for
the country's six-month presidency of the European Union, which begins
tomorrow, insisting that it went no further than what was agreed by all
other member states.
'We will do everything in our power to promote the cause of Europe in this
limited period,' he told the Bundestag in Bonn.
Mr Hurd will hold talks in London today with Mr Kinkel. But the foreign
secretary refused to list the potential candidates for Mr Delors' post.
Diplomats in Brussels are mentioning three names in particular for the
presidency: Mr Felipe Gonzalez, the Spanish prime minister, Mr Anbal Cavaco
Silva, his Portuguese counterpart, and Mr Giuliano Amato, the former prime
minister of Italy.
