<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 94 / Enterprise cash raid snaps up 9.8 per cent of Lasmo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE and DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Enterprise Oil raised the stakes in its long-running bid for Lasmo yesterday
by buying nearly 10 per cent of Lasmo's stock from its largest shareholder
for cash.
The deal, clinched in a long-awaited raid timed to coincide with the opening
of Wall Street, angered other shareholders who are being offered only
Enterprise shares and warrants under the terms of the bid.
The Pounds 1.6bn takeover offer, which aims to create a prominent new oil
exploration and production company, has hung in the balance for several
weeks, but the Enterprise raid was intended to wrest advantage just ahead of
the bid deadline at 1pm tomorrow.
However, some institutional shareholders in Lasmo remain undecided, and
analysts last night said the bid was still too close to call.
Phillips &amp; Drew Fund Management, Lasmo's biggest shareholder, confirmed last
night that it had sold 77m shares at 169p a share. It sold the shares hours
after a meeting with senior Lasmo executives. However, PDFM still holds half
of its original 16 per cent holding, and the decision it will announce today
on how that will be voted will be crucial.
Enterprise bought 9.8 per cent of Lasmo shares in two tranches. It said
86.8m shares, which includes those bought from PDFM, were purchased at 169p
a share and 7.77m at 161p.
Mr Rudolph Agnew, Lasmo chairman, said the purchase made the paper offer -
of 36 new Enterprise A shares and 13 warrants for every 88 Lasmo shares -
worthless.
He told Reuters: 'This means the rest of the City are left with a junk paper
offer and they would be well advised not to accept it.'
Some institutions and private shareholders were angry at yesterday's
developments. One private investor who complained to the Takeover Panel
said: 'Every shareholder apart from a lucky few will suffer.'
The Takeover Panel took no action after the raid because it did not appear
to have breached the takeover rules. The fact that Enterprise's raid was
paid for in cash rather than Enterprise paper did not matter so long as the
value was the same.
The rules also permit a bidder to buy up to 10 per cent of the target
company's stock.
Analysts said Enterprise could have jeopardised its bid by antagonising
institutions that were unable to take advantage of the cash offer.
On balance, though, it appeared to have ended up in a stronger position. By
buying half of Phillips &amp; Drew Fund Management's stake, it has reduced the
size of Lasmo's biggest shareholder and gained control of a useful portion
of its quarry's stock.
Lasmo's shares remained firm at 144p, and Enterprise's fell 27p to 381p.
