<PROFILE>_AN-EF3D2AH8FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940629
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / International Company News: Deckel Maho near bankrupt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Deckel Maho, one of Germany's largest machine tool companies, is on the
verge of declaring itself bankrupt.
Mr Werner Schneider, appointed receiver to the Bavaria-based group after it
filed for protection against creditors in April, said that a formal
application for bankruptcy was the next legal step after it had proved
impossible to work out a solution with creditors to guarantee the group's
survival.
Mr Schneider said, however, that he was hopeful that it would be possible to
rescue the group - which owes banks DM530m (Dollars 325.1m) - through a sale
to a third party.
Discussions are taking place with Traub and Gildemeister, two German
machine-tool rivals, but neither company has made a firm offer, Mr Schneider
indicated. It would be necessary to cut the workforce by 500 or 600 from
1,700 this week and next, he said.
Deckel Maho is itself the product of a merger between two family-controlled
south-German manufacturers. This took place last summer on the initiative of
Deutsche Bank and Bayerische Vereinsbank in the hope that the merged group
would better be able to withstand the severe downturn in the German
machine-tools sector.
In July last year, the combined group predicted that it would return to
profits in three years after an aggressive cost-cutting programme.
However, in the year to June 1 1994, turnover was DM340m to DM345m,
considerably below planned sales of DM400m, while at the end of May the
order book amounted to DM70m, just 2 1/2 months' production. Between 1990
and 1994, the two groups shed 3,000 jobs and combined turnover more than
halved.
Mr Schneider said that Deckel Maho shares were worthless in view of the
group's heavy indebtedness. The takeover by a third party would involve a
write-off of existing debt or the conversion of debt into equity, coupled
with an injection of fresh capital from the new owner.
</TEXT>
