<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / International Company News: Moulinex sets terms of capital
increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Moulinex, the French household appliances group, yesterday announced the
terms of its FFr1bn (Dollars 185m) capital increase, saying it would issue
two new shares for three existing ones, at a price of FFr90 a share.
Although long-expected, details of the capital increase pushed shares in the
indebted company down FFr5.3 to FFr122.
Under the terms of the capital increase, for which subscriptions will be
open from July 5 to July 25, Financiere Moulinex DCSM, the holding company,
and Finap, the group subsidiary, will subscribe to FFr404m of the capital
increase. The balance will be offered to the public. The offer is being
underwritten by a consortium of banks led by Credit Lyonnais.
In a separate operation, the holding company will raise FFr500m, bringing in
a number of financial partners chosen over the past few months to support
the company's restructuring.
Following the capital increase, Euris, a consortium of investors, will hold
33 per cent of the holding company. The holding company, combined with
Finap, in turn will hold 28.8 per cent of Moulinex, with employees holding
10.8 per cent and the public just under 60 per cent.
The complex capital restructuring follows a period of protracted
negotiations aimed at reinforcing Moulinex's financial structure. The
company has been hit by the European recession and by the burden of debts
incurred as a result of its acquisition of Krups, a German competitor, in
1991.
Moulinex suffered losses of FFr598m in the financial year to the end of
March 1993, compared with net profits of FFr41m for the same period in the
previous year.
The French government said yesterday that it had appointed Credit Commercial
de France and the French subsidiary of J. P. Morgan of the US as advisers
for the privatisation of Assurances Generales de France.
AGF, one of France's largest insurers, is next on the list of 21
publicly-owned groups slated for privatisation and the operation is expected
to take place after the summer. But no date has been set for the sale and
the timing will depend on market conditions.
See World Stock Markets
</TEXT>
