FT  29 JUN 94 / Drugs company chief quits over share scandal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Nippon Shoji, a Japanese drug wholesaler and distributor whose employees are
being investigated for alleged insider trading, said yesterday its president
will step down to take responsibility for the scandal.
Company employees face charges that they used confidential information about
the deaths of patients using its shingles drug. The Securities and Exchange
Surveillance Commission, the securities watchdog, is conducting an
investigation.
Some 175 workers and family members are believed to have sold Nippon Shoji
shares before the health and welfare ministry publicly disclosed last
October the fatal side effects of Sorivudine, the company's treatment,
launched in September last year.
Mr Takakazu Hattori will resign to become the company's consultant, while Mr
Masami Shimizu, vice president, will take his place. The move follows the
company's dismissal of four former executives on Monday over allegations of
illicit stock trading.
</TEXT>
