<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / FT Review of Business Books (25): Signposts in all
directions - Transport Policy / Charles Batchelor finds helpful hints along
the way
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Transport &amp; Planning
by David Banister E &amp; FN Spon, Pounds 39 248 pages
A new bypass cutting through attractive countryside; the time it takes get
to work or to the shops by train or bus; the privatisation of British Rail.
Few subjects are calculated to stir a heated debate as those relating to
transport.
Transport Planning does not set out to provide an answer to the questions
prompted by government transport policies - or the lack of them. But in
attempting to trace the evolution of transport planning and its relationship
to policy decisions, it provides some helpful hints along the way.
David Banister follows the development of postwar transport thinking from
the days of 'predict and provide', when planners drew up road plans with the
simple aim of accommodating projected traffic growth.
This approach was being challenged by some forward thinking individuals in
the early 1960s. But the long lead-times involved in transport projects and
the mesmerising effect of the car on planners and politicians meant it took
more than a decade before the change in attitudes began to work its way
through.
As the 1970s progressed, greater weight was given to public transport and
planners began to act on the realisation that new roads not only absorbed
existing demand but generated increased car use.
In parallel with this came a radical shift in the approach taken by
politicians towards a more deregulated environment where the market decided.
Like many members of the travelling public, Banister, director of the
planning and research centre at University College, London, has his doubts
about the results of this change. He questions the value of bus
deregulation, which has served to speed up the gradual fall in bus use, and
the privatisation of British Rail.
The problem for those who argue for a greater role for public transport is
the overwhelming attractiveness of the car. The basis on which people plan
their lives, with home often far from the place of work, and attitudes to
car ownership has changed radically over the past three decades. It will be
hard to persuade people back on to public transport.
Yet unrestricted growth in the use of the car threatens irreparable damage
to the environment. A strategic vision and a planning framework are required
to allocate resources and choose priorities, Banister suggests.
The problem for successive British governments is that transport policy is
driven by conflicting requirements to reduce environmental damage, curb the
demands of transport on budget resources and preserve freedom for the car
owner. This confusion has not helped the government's attempts to involve
more private capital in the building of transport infrastructure.
The private sector wants low risk projects which have a short pay-back
period and provide a good return. Yet most transport projects have long
pay-back periods and low rates of return. They involve large capital
investments at the outset and are often subject to cost overruns. The
government cannot expect to withdraw completely, Banister warns.
Lack of an all-embracing policy framework has not slowed the pace of
transport initiatives. Recent months have seen a reduction in the motorway
building programme and the announcement of new planning guidelines to curb
the growth of out-of-town developments. The pace of recent change makes this
a timely book.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
