<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / FT Review of Business Books (24): Driving force behind
capitalism - Technological Innovation / Andrew Fisher is fascinated by
inventors and their times
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Exploring the Black Box, Technology, Economics and History
by Nathan Rosenberg, Cambridge University Press Pounds 40 hardback, Pounds
14.95 paperback 274 pages
Innovation, the process by which the 'black box' of the title is created,
can be fascinating and fruitful or arduous and frustrating. Sometimes, it
can be all of these. For while technological innovation is vital to economic
advancement, the route to success is anything but straightforward.
In Professor Nathan Rosenberg's book, it is made abundantly clear that
innovation can bring either pain or reward, probably more of the former.
Innovations can be premature so that the pioneers may fail to reap the
profits which are then garnered by those coming later - in such cases, the
products may be technologically brilliant but not yet economically ripe.
Innovations can also go unrecognised so that companies miss the boat. A
telling example cited by Rosenberg, professor of economics at Stanford
University, is that of Western Union which was offered Alexander Graham
Bell's telephone patent for Dollars 100,000 in 1877 but turned it down.
Apparently, it did not regard the telephone as an adequate substitute for
the telegraph.
Inventors and innovators themselves may underestimate or wrongly assess the
value of their breakthroughs. Guglielmo Marconi, for example, did not
foresee how widely radio could be applied in mass communications. Computers,
in their early days, were generally seen as having only limited research
applications.
Another intriguing point made by Rosenberg concerns innovators themselves.
'Major inventions are frequently the work of outsiders - people whose
conceptual frameworks and training are not defined by and limited to the
prevailing technology.' Bell was a teacher of the deaf, Marconi had little
technological training of any sort and Samuel Morse had been a portrait
painter before inventing the telegraph.
All three produced their own versions of the 'black box' which Rosenberg
uses as a metaphor for the mysteries and benefits of technology.
In fact, the book's title is rather more catchy than his treatment of the
subject. (Some chapters developed from earlier papers are written with
collaborators.) His chief aim is to show how innovation proceeds from the
economic, social and scientific background of the time.
Thus the book is not a management manual or a guide for businessmen seeking
advice on how to translate ideas into commercial success.
It is a serious, challenging and often fascinating study - by no means a
relaxing read - of how complex technologies arise and find their way along a
tortuous and obstacle-strewn route to the market.
The book follows an earlier one called Inside the Black Box in which
Rosenberg sought to examine its contents. In this one, he is trying to
establish how they got there in the first place. He analyses, in historical,
economic and technological terms, the processes by which information comes
to pervade new technologies.
Two of the most fascinating chapters in the book are about Charles Babbage,
whose calculating engine was an early precursor of the computer, and Joseph
Schumpeter, the Austrian economist who wrote of the 'perennial gale of
creative destruction' to which capitalist economies are subject.
Rosenberg regards Babbage as a pioneer in the analysis of technological
change. He seeks to rehabilitate him from what he calls his 'furtive, almost
fugitive existence in the literature of economics'.
Babbage, whose book, On the Economy of Machinery and Manufactures, was
published in 1833, wrote from a deep knowledge of the newly developing
mechanical age.
Schumpeter's contribution to the debate on innovation was to show that this
was a driving force behind the very progress of capitalism. He described
capitalism as 'by nature a form or method of economic change' which never is
and never can be stationary.
He also believed in the primacy of economic history, regarding this as more
important than theory or statistics.
As well as delving into the history of technological change and analysis,
Rosenberg looks separately and in considerable depth at innovation in the
energy, chemical, telecommunications and forest products industries. But
while these chapters are undoubtedly valuable, it is the broader concepts
developed in the first half of the book that are likely to interest most
readers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
