<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / FT Review of Business Books (22): Notable newcomers - Inward
Investment / Roland Adburgham looks at the Japanese in Wales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Working for the Japanese: The Economic and Social Consequences of Japanese
Investment in Wales
by Jonathan Morris, Max Munday and Barry Wilkinson Athlone Press, Pounds 32,
156 pages
With some justification, Wales has prided itself on its success at winning
inward investment to help to counter the contraction of its traditional
heavy industries. Notable among the newcomers have been Japanese
manufacturers. It is more than 20 years since the first of these, Takiron,
arrived. Today, they number more than 40, including names such as Sony,
Sharp, Matsushita and Toyota.
From the start, they sparked controversy with their novel (at the time)
single union and no-strike agreements and innovative management practices.
They were criticised for being assembly-type operations exploiting the
labour surplus in Wales to create a largely female, low-skilled workforce.
While such issues stimulated broad debate, there has been less analysis of
the overall value to Wales of the newcomers. This book, by three members of
the Japanese Management Research Unit of Cardiff Business School, is a
useful assessment of their impact.
The authors conclude that, although Japanese companies employ only 1 per
cent of the Welsh workforce, the effect has been both considerable and
beneficial - 'Undoubtedly, Wales would be a poorer place without the
Japanese.'
One consequence, they say, is that Welsh employers have been spurred to
develop a 'Japanese-style' of working, 'centring on individual
responsibility for product quality, team working and functional
flexibility'.
Over the years, the nature of the plants has changed: the second wave of
newcomers saw fewer assembly-only plants and more original equipment
manufacturers. Later arrivals included component manufacturers, supplying
the existing plants.
The authors find that 'plants are developing away from the assembly-only
stereotype and are employing, in some cases, large numbers of managers and
engineers'.
But they point out that only a minority of plants carry out research or
design work and investment remains concentrated in a narrow industry segment
 -consumer electronics and office automation. And, they say, 'it is clear
that the boom in Japanese investment that occurred during the mid to late
1980s is largely over'.
The authors' researches throw up many intriguing facts. Government aid has
worked out at about Pounds 7,500 per worker. Although one company reported
1,500 people on its recruitment waiting list, many businesses reported
difficulties in finding engineering staff and technicians. Younger employees
are becoming a smaller proportion of the workforces, as their employers
realise the value of more mature staff.
The companies are beginning to play a corporate-citizen role in the
community. Managers from Japan say they much appreciate the warm welcome
received in Wales and enjoy the working environment. The negative factors
for them are education of children, language problems and their wives'
integration into the local community. One manager complained: 'No hot
springs, no bar hopping, no ladies]'
In spite of the book's title, there is little about the attitude of the
workers. The Welsh workforce, we are told, 'has adapted with remarkably
little resistance or complaint to a Japanese style of working', a fact
attributed to personnel and industrial relations practices. But we do not
learn whether the Welsh prefer to work for the Japanese.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
