<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / FT Review of Business Books (19): No solution perfect -
Corporate Governance / Geoffrey Owen looks at contrasting systems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEOFFREY OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Capital Markets and Corporate Governance
Edited by Nicholas Dimsdale and Martha Prevezer Oxford University Press,
Pounds 40 349 pages
The objectives of any system of corporate governance are to organise
relationships between owners, boards of directors and management in a way
which promotes the long-term growth and profitability of the enterprise.
The form which these relationships take varies widely among the industrial
countries and none has found a perfect solution. Most of the 16 papers
edited by Nicholas Dimsdale and Martha Prevezer deal with deficiencies in
British arrangements, including the allegedly malign effects of excessive
takeover activity and 'short-termism.' But the book also contains some
useful comparisons with Japan and Germany, which have problems of their own.
Differences between the three countries - in the composition of boards, in
the pattern of share ownership, in the role of banks - stem from historical
circumstances. In Japan, for example, the capital liberalisation which began
in 1967 promoted companies to protect themselves against foreign takeover
through cross-shareholdings. With more than half their company's equity in
the hands of stable, long-term shareholders, Japanese managers worry much
less about the share price than their counterparts in the US and Britain.
As Colin Mayer points out, Japanese and German systems of ownership and
control are not directed exclusively to the interests of shareholders, but
involve other stakeholders in decision-making, including suppliers,
purchasers, banks and employees.
In Japan, according to Seiichi Masuyama, 'stable shareholders are selected
by and are dependent on management, and cannot therefore play a disciplinary
role on corporate management'. The main source of disciplinary pressure, he
suggests, comes from the need to satisfy employees.
Jenny Corbett notes that Japanese boards are dominated by executive
directors who are promoted from within: 'It is not clear how shareholders
can remove or replace poor managers nor how they can force managers to look
after their interests.'
In principle, the monitoring problem should be handled more efficiently in
Germany, where there is a clear separation between management and
supervision. But supervisory boards meet only three or four times a year and
their members are often too remote from the company's affairs to exert
effective influence; their input, according to a survey reported by Jeremy
Edwards and Klaus Fischer, is far less than that of US non-executive
directors, partly because of the importance in the US of board committees,
especially the audit committee.
Recent failures of German corporate governance have raised doubts about the
'insider' approach to corporate control; there have been calls for the
appointment of genuinely independent directors, with no business ties to the
company.
How these independent directors should be appointed, and what incentives
they might have for rigorous monitoring of management, is one of the
unsolved problems of the Anglo-American system. For Allen Sykes the way
forward is for institutional shareholders to agree among themselves that
every major company would have three to five 'core' investors, which would
hold the shares for at least five years and be directly represented on the
board. Their combined shareholding would normally amount to 15-20 per cent
of the equity. Each of the top 60 institutions would take a special interest
in, on average, eight of the top 100 companies. They would be free to trade
without restriction in the other 92.
Any move in this direction would require an unlikely degree of common
purpose on the part of shareholders. British and American institutional
investors have been intervening more vigorously in badly managed companies.
But this hardly amounts to large, committed shareholdings on the Japanese or
German pattern.
How much do these differences in corporate governance matter? Many
commentators deplore the absence of trust and commitment in the
Anglo-American system. But the regeneration of the US motor industry over
the past decade suggests that some Japanese management practices, including
high-trust relationships with suppliers and employees, can be adopted within
the constraints of US financial markets.
German and Japanese institutional arrangements have some important
strengths, but dispersed shareholdings and an active takeover market may not
be quite as serious a competitive disadvantage as most contributors to this
volume assume.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
