<PROFILE>_AN-EF2DYAHGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940629
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / FT Review of Business Books (14): In Plato's footsteps -
Technopols / The question of whether political systems govern economic
success is a sticky one
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LUBIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Political Economy of Policy Reform
Edited by John Williamson Institute of International Economics Pounds 9.99
93 pages
What conditions are needed for a government to implement economic reform
successfully?
The knee-jerk response to this is to drum up an image of an authoritarian
government taking power during an economic crisis, acting quickly and using
all the means at its disposal, including violence, to silence any opposition
to the policies it knows it must rigorously pursue despite all the
short-term costs. Does that answer the question?
Partly. Those conditions - which more or less describe Pinochet's Chile, for
example - might be sufficient for a government to implement reforms, but
they are not necessary. At least that is the sensible conclusion of John
Williamson's book from the Institute for International Economics. Williamson
doesn't bring us much closer to knowing what is both sufficient and
necessary. But that says less about the quality of his book than the
slipperiness of the subject.
The book, which has grown out of a conference held last year on these
issues, draws together 13 essays by a group of authors that Williamson calls
'technopols' - policy-makers who start off life as technically skilled
functionaries (armed almost always with an economics PhD from a US
university?), unconnected to any vested interests, whose only political
commitment is to their vision of the common good. On this definition, they
are probably the nearest substitute the modern world has for Plato's
philosopher-kings.
Eleven of the 13 give accounts of successful episodes of economic reform,
and two - Luiz Carlos Bresser Pereira, Brazil's finance minister in 1987,
and Richard Webb, Peru's central bank governor in the early 1980s - try to
say why they could not make reforms stick. These essays have a tendency to
dissolve into acts of self-justification, and some of them could have had a
bit less 'pol' and a bit more 'techno'. In one essay, for example, Jose
Pinera, who was at different times Pinochet's minister for labour and for
social security, fails to mention his government's suppression of dissent,
and thus creates a loud silence which mars an otherwise interesting piece.
Readers looking for a user's guide for policy-makers will find this book
disappointing. Every time you think you have come across the political sine
qua non of economic reform, a counter-example pops up to frustrate you. You
might start off thinking, for example, that authoritarian regimes headed by
visionary leaders must have an advantage over democratic ones, only to
discover that plenty of democratic governments - Portugal in 1985, Colombia
in 1989, Poland in 1990 - have implemented successful reform packages, and
plenty of authoritarian ones have not.
The book tries to test a number of hypotheses like this. Are a government's
chances of success better in the midst of an economic crisis? Or in the
'honeymoon' period at the start of an administration? Commonsense suggests
that they must be, since a crisis creates the sort of shock needed to wear
down resistance to change, and a 'honeymoon' hands the benefit of the doubt
to a new regime. But honeymoons and crises are not always ingredients of
successful reforms, as you learn by bearing in mind that Colombia's 1989
reforms were begun just a few months before the end of President
Barco'sadministration in an atmosphere of relative calm.
Perhaps the biggest drawback of the book is that apples in one country are
too frequently compared with pears in another. Arguably it just doesn't make
sense to compare Colombia's reforms in 1989, for example, to Poland's in
1990, since completely different goals were being pursued. In Poland, the
aim was a fundamental re-ordering of society, against which Colombia's
reforms appear to have been mere tinkering. Naturally, the political
conditions that made each reform possible were different, since the type of
reform being implemented was different. A more complete book would have
resulted if some attention had been paid to this.
Only one condition stands out as being a feature of every successful reform
episode the book describes: the presence of a united and coherent economic
team in charge of designing the reform programme. What lessons come from
this? Should we, after all, hand over our destinies to the technopols? At
least Plato would approve.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
