<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / FT Review of Business Books (12): Mexican prospects - NAFTA
/ Stephen Fidler looks at views on the trade agreement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For Richer, For Poorer: Shaping US-Mexican Integration
by Harry Browne Latin America Bureau, Pounds 7.99 128 pages
Mexico: Industrial Development Review: The Promise of Nafta
United Nations Industrial Development Organisation Economist Intelligence
Unit Pounds 95 (Dollars 150 in US and Asia) 222 pages
Here are two very different books looking at the same issue: the economic
consequences of the North American Free Trade Agreement and the increasing
economic integration between Mexico and the US.
The first describes sympathetically many of the arguments deployed in
opposition to Nafta, which joined the US, Mexico and Canada in a free trade
area which came into effect at the start of this year envisaging the
elimination of all trade barriers between the three countries over a 15-year
period.
The second is the latest of the country reviews of industrial development
produced by the United Nations Industrial Development Organisation and
published by the EIU which examines the ability of Mexico to compete in its
new North American environment.
For Richer, For Poorer typifies much of the muddled debate over Nafta. Its
underlying premise is that the agreement is essentially a charter allowing
large corporations to exploit cheap Mexican labour and lax environmental
regulation and to keep down US wages.
The implicit suggestion that Nafta ignores the needs of dynamic small and
medium-sized businesses on both sides of the border is an interesting one
that deserves further examination, but that's not what we are treated to.
Instead, a work full of contradictions suggests that Mexico's Dollars 280bn
economy will inflict huge economic damage on the Dollars 6,000bn US economy
and on American workers. What's more, as far as one can gather, it will do
so without producing any appreciable benefit to the Mexican economy or the
people who work in it.
The premise is that Nafta will encourage US companies to move to Mexico, but
that Mexican workers will not benefit because Nafta 'contained no mechanisms
that would allow them to resist their government's repressive, low-wage
strategy'.
This refers to the government's domination of the Mexican trade unions which
benefits corporations at the expense of workers. Evidence that Mexican
workers will not benefit from Nafta is the 20-40 per cent fall in real wages
they suffered between 1982 and 1991 - a peak-to-trough comparison
incorporating the years of the debt crisis.
Meanwhile, US workers will suffer even as labour productivity increases.
This is because the theory of comparative advantage - that overall welfare
increases when countries make the things they produce most efficiently and
trade them freely - does not work in the real-world absence of its perfect
market assumptions.
The evidence for this also comes from the 1980s where real manufacturing
wages declined 5-10 per cent. 'Although the number of jobs in the economy
increased by over 20m during the decade and the unemployment rate fell,
workers' incomes barely improved,' it says, as if the creation of 20m jobs
benefits nobody.
The inconsistencies are manifold and evidence used to illustrate one point
is contradicted to make another. For example, while it argues that Mexicans
won't benefit from the low wages to be paid by US companies, it makes the
point elsewhere that it is not only low-paid, low-skill jobs that will
migrate to Mexico.
The initial flavour of academic impartiality is quickly cast aside. Nafta,
though it came into effect but months ago, is somehow connected to the
terrible performance of Mexican agriculture which has turned the country
from being a net exporter of agricultural products into a net importer.
The drawbacks of the maquila system of in-bond manufacturing in place since
1965 - US companies establish manufacturing plants in Mexico and can import
their inputs duty-free providing they export the manufactured result - are
insinuated to be the same drawbacks of Nafta.
The spillover benefits of the maquiladora industry to the Mexican economy
have been limited, it is true. But under Nafta, the maquiladoras - which
earned an estimated Dollars 5bn in foreign exchange in 1993 - will be phased
out. As the UNIDO report points out, Nafta will remove the obstacles to the
maquiladoras' use of Mexican inputs and should help their integration into
the Mexican economy.
The UNIDO publication is both duller and better researched. It argues
electronic, food processing, motor vehicle, petrochemical and textile
industries in Mexico all stand to benefit from Nafta. Among maquilas, those
using Japanese and other foreign components will benefit least. Overall, it
estimates Nafta will lead to the creation of 600,000 new jobs in Mexico by
1995 - and an increase in wage rates.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT942-301</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EF2DYAHDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940629
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / FT Review of Business Books (11): Lions lie down with lambs
 -German Economy / Christopher Huhne on a left-of-centre viewpoint
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER HUHNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Reshaping of the German Social Market
by David Goodhart Institute for Public Policy Research, Pounds 7.50 83 pages
The Germans gave us the word Schadenfreude - delight in others' misfortunes
 -but this ignoble sentiment is by no means confined to its country of
origin. Indeed, the Germans themselves have recently become the butt of
rather too much Schadenfreude from their Anglo- Saxon cousins, some of whom
relish the difficulties faced by the hitherto miraculous German economy.
Reports of Germany's demise, however, are premature. Much of that analysis,
spurred by the Germans' own taste for self-doubt, is no more than the
product of the business cycle and the transient difficulties of
reunification. Germany is emerging from a prolonged and deep recession, a
time during which it is easy to gain an audience for the proposition that
the present gloom will extend for ever. Yet the pessimists are usually just
as wide of the mark as the optimists who see economic rejuvenation at the
top of every boom.
The truth is more interesting, as David Goodhart argues in a
thought-provoking review of the German experience. The German model - what
Michel Albert called the Rhine model of capitalism and what the Germans call
the social market - is under strain. Its social safety net is being tested
by an ageing population and the collapse of employment in the eastern Lander
caused by monetary union at an ill-judged exchange rate.
Germany's industries are facing low-wage competition not only from Asian
newly-industrialising countries, but also from closer to home in Silesia,
Bohemia and Moravia. Its reputation for fiscal orthodoxy has taken a
battering at the hands of sky-high budget deficits.
It is at least arguable, Goodhart concedes, that Germany's skills in
mechanical engineering and a natural bent for incremental improvement were
appropriate to a second industrial revolution of cars and consumer goods
rather than the third revolution of science and technology.
But German strengths should not be underestimated. This is a country with
345 industries that have a world market share of more than 10 per cent.
Germany's wage-bargaining system has also delivered a fall in unit wage
costs of 6 per cent since the start of 1993, an example of wage flexibility
unparalleled in other European labour markets.
There is, of course, a lot of politics wrapped up in all this. Goodhart is
writing for a left-of-centre think tank and has set out to recapture the
German social market as an example for social democrats rather than the
Thatcherite right.
He is persuasive. Germany is indeed characterised by a large number of
institutions and relationships that Anglo-Saxon liberals of the well-brought
up variety find intrinsically shocking.
Lambs lie down with lions in the supervisory boards of German companies and
this flirtation with corporatism extends through banks that own large slices
of companies, centralised wage bargaining between employers and big
sector-wide trade unions and employers' organisations that set training
goals. Where Anglo-Saxons expect conflict, Germans serve up a puzzling
degree of co-operation.
Goodhart points out that firms benefit from a relationship of trust with
their employees because they can invest in their knowledge and skills with
less fear that they will walk out of the door.
If Goodhart's analysis is to be faulted, it is that he does not lay enough
stress on another aspect of the German model which may be less to the liking
of the British left.
Post-war Germany has been fiercely committed to competition in product
markets, enforced by an admirably tough competition in law and by an
aggressive Bundescartelamt that makes the Monopolies and Mergers Commission
look as dangerous as an overfed tabbycat.
With some notable exceptions in declining industries such as coal, Germany
has also been thankfully immune from the belief that the government can
usefully intervene in industry.
Goodhart contends that Germany's style of capitalism will endure in spite of
a gradual breakdown of union influence and widening pay differentials, some
withdrawal of the banks from their position in corporate governance, a rise
in the influence of the equity market and a shift of much high-labour
content production outside Germany together with the growth of real German
multinationals. Within Germany, the relatively small service sector ought to
be able to grow rapidly to take up the slack.
But what of the lessons on this side of the Channel? Britain's economic
institutions have been travelling rapidly away from the Rhine model and
towards the US one over the past decade, but that may not continue to be the
case. Goodhart cites interesting evidence about the preferences of British
managers for a 'stakeholder' company suggesting UK attitudes may be more in
line with Germany than with the US.
Goodhart rightly warns against too glib an import of German institutions,
but he sets out three policy options that might nudge Britain in Germany's
direction. The first is encouragement to institutional investors, which own
more than 70 per cent of quoted Britain, to take a more active role in the
companies they own, as the German banks do.
The second is the introduction of supervisory boards with employee
representatives. The third is to boost the training and enterprise councils
 -now responsible for much of Britain's training effort - by making
corporate membership compulsory for companies above a certain size.
By the standards of recent years, these are radical proposals. But I doubt
that the relative performance of Britain and Germany over the next 10 years
will expunge them from the agenda. The Rhine model is not new. Its essential
features were in place under Bismarck. It has delivered Europe's most
enduring economic success for over a century and it is unlikely to stop now.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT942-302</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EF2DYAHCFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940629
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / FT Review of Business Books (10): Enigma of the Reichmanns
remains - Property / Vanessa Houlder finds no new insights in an account of
the O&amp;Y saga
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Too Big to Fail
by Walter Stewart McClelland &amp; Stewart, Pounds 15.95 335 pages
In essence, the story of Olympia &amp; York's rise and fall is an
all-too-familiar account of how an ambitious company can be brought to the
brink of bankruptcy by the reckless pursuit of growth. But it gains an extra
dimension from the enigmatic personality of the three Reichmann brothers who
founded, managed and owned the company.
The Reichmanns built up one of the world's largest property empires with a
style that set them apart from brasher, pushier developers. They won a name
for honesty, privacy, and discretion that matched their reputation for
innovation, farsightedness and daring.
But once O&amp;Y buckled under the burden of its Pounds 7bn debt in 1992, the
Reichmanns' name and reputation were tarnished. Frustrated creditors felt
they had been misled by the brothers once they discovered the true state of
their empire.
A disappointing aspect of Stewart's book is that he never assesses the
extent to which the Reichmanns' reputation for ethical business dealings was
deserved. Instead, he is sympathetic to the point of sycophancy. 'O&amp;Y are
wonderful managers, superior builders, and all-around worthwhile people,' he
says in the prologue.
Stewart's sympathy for the Reichmanns did not open doors. He admits that he
met 'an unbroken wall of brass' in attempts to talk to O&amp;Y and the Reichmann
family. The result is that the book contains little new material and largely
recounts publicly-available information.
Nonetheless, his outline of their rise and fall makes a remarkable story. It
begins with the brothers' early lives in Hungary, Austria and Morocco, where
their mother, Renee, was the Tangier agent of a committee devoted to
rescuing Jews trapped by the Nazis.
In the 1950s, the family moved to Canada, where Paul and Ralph Reichmann set
up the Olympia Floor and Wall Tile Company (Ontario) with capital of Dollars
50,000. After building a warehouse for the company, they successfully moved
into property development.
O&amp;Y's ambitions were not limited to property. In 1979, it bought Canada
Northwest Land, an oil and gas company; in 1981, O&amp;Y took control of
Abitibi-Price, then the world's biggest newspaper producer; four years
later, it bought a 60 per cent stake in Gulf Oil's Canadian subsidiary, then
the biggest corporate takeover in Canadian history; in 1986, it took control
of Hiram Walker, the drinks and resources group.
O&amp;Y's evolution into a major financial conglomerate was, Stewart suggests, a
step too far for a company still run as a small family firm dominated by
three men. But it was property, O&amp;Y's original area of expertise, that
proved its undoing.
In 1987 the Reichmanns poured Pounds 1.4bn into a pioneering development in
a remote part of east London, encouraged by generous tax breaks and with the
backing of Margaret Thatcher, then Britain's prime minister.
This proved disastrous. The Reichmanns struggled to attract tenants, in the
face of recession, to an area that was unfavourably perceived and poorly
served by public transport, amid an explosion of construction elsewhere in
London.
While Canary Wharf struggled, O&amp;Y sunk into deep trouble on the other side
of the Atlantic because of its exposure to the Campeau retail empire, which
met difficulties after an over-ambitious takeover of two of the US's biggest
department store groups. At the same time, other parts of the O&amp;Y empire,
such as Abitibi-Price and Gulf Canada absorbed large amounts of cash.
On May 14, O&amp;Y applied for bankruptcy protection. Following months of
wrangling a restructuring was agreed in Toronto in January 1993, that would
eventually dismantle much of the empire.
This adequate account of the story does not live up to its subtitle: Olympia
&amp; York: the story behind the headlines. Indeed, it often reads as a critique
of other writers' assessments of O&amp;Y.
Stewart's one-time career as a professor of journalism may explain his
pre-occupation with flaws in accounts written by his rivals, but in a book
so dependent on other people's research and marred by minor errors of its
own, it only serves to irritate.
Nonetheless, Stewart makes some cogent points when he blames the failure of
the O&amp;Y empire largely on the financial and political system. 'What happened
to O&amp;Y has less to do with the personalities of the Reichmanns . . . than it
has to do with the laws governing incorporation, taxation, banking and
bankruptcy.'
O&amp;Y's acquisitiveness was encouraged by Canada's tax laws; its
over-ambitious expansion was fuelled by credulous banks.
When it came to the crunch, the bankruptcy laws protected a company that was
deemed 'too big to fail'. The O&amp;Y debacle did severe damage to the company's
creditors, but it did not ruin the Reichmanns. Two days after the
restructuring of O&amp;Y was approved, Paul Reichmann was back in business with
plans to invest in North American commercial property.
</TEXT>
