<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / FT Review of Business Books (9): Four ways ahead - Strategic
Management / PN Thornton on a self-effacing prizewinner
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PN THORNTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
What is Strategy and Does it Matter?
by Richard Whittington Routledge, Pounds 39 164 pages
There are 37 books in print with the title Strategic Management, according
to Richard Whittington in the introduction to this rather self-effacingly
titled little volume in the Routledge series in analytical management.
So who needs a 38th? The answer, of course, is all those who either lack the
time or the retentive capacity to cope with the other 37. Not that
Whittington's book relieves its readers of the burden of informing
themselves more widely, nor indeed does it claim to do so.
What it does seek to do is to map out the landscape of contemporary
approaches to strategy-making, and to provide a guided tour of that
landscape. Readers should then be in a position to decide which approach is
most appropriate to their own circumstances, and to know where to turn for
more detailed guidance.
In this aim it succeeds, at least in the opinion of the judging panel for
the Management Consultancies Association Business Book of the Year. It
carried off the first prize for the best business book of the year by a
British author aged under 45.
Whittington's framework consists of a 2x2 matrix (how else]) within which
any approach to strategy can be slotted. The axes of the matrix represent
the top-down (deliberate) or bottom-up (emergent) process used to arrive at
a strategy on the one hand and the profit-maximising or more broadly based
pluralistic objectives of the strategy on the other.
Within this matrix, four basic approaches are identified. The classical
approach, associated with renowned authorities such as Ansoff and Porter
adopts a deliberate process of rational analysis designed to maximise
long-term advantage. Evolutionists, on the other hand, eschew long-term
planning as largely irrelevant in today's fast-changing world. All that one
can do is to operate as efficiently as possible in today's conditions, and
take tomorrow as it comes. Natural selection will determine who survives and
who goes under.
Processualists such as Mintzberg and Hamel agree that long-range planning is
largely futile, and that organisations evolve through a process of trial and
error. However, this incremental approach is not necessarily just a tactical
one; it may be informed by an underlying 'strategic intent' which provides a
broad sense of direction and channels opportunism.
Finally, Whittington himself favours a systemic point of view, which
recognises that the objectives of an organisation can vary dramatically,
depending on the culture (national culture, in the main) within which it is
embedded.
He notes, for example, that Japanese companies target themselves on market
share and new product introductions whereas US companies are focused heavily
on return on investment and share price.
Having defined his terms (and the book is worth reading for this alone,
though some plain words would have helped) Whittington examines a number of
important elements of modern management - leadership, decision-making,
approaches to growth and organisational change.
He does this through the 'lens' of each of his four basic schools of
strategic thinking. The classical approach to decision-making, for example,
will rely heavily on detailed analysis, whereas the processualists believe
this creates a delusion that one is shaping the future.
The systemic school takes a more cynical view. If analysis is expected to
get the decision, do it; it not, don't. And not surprisingly Whittington
concludes that strategy, or rather the approach to strategy does matter, for
the whole economy as well as for individual enterprises.
He argues that the 'market-rational' paradigm adopted by the Anglo-Saxon
world is deficient, and that future success will require greater state
leadership and some interlocking of national and business strategies.
This sounds over-simplistic, and it is. But that does not detract from the
overall merit of the book, which is well-structured, short and energetically
written. It does, though, deal with some challenging material (the author is
an academic with Warwick Business School) and it is not an easy read.
However, it repays perseverance, and all those concerned with strategy
development, whether as consultants, business development executives or
general managers, should end up with an enriched understanding of what
strategy means for them and which approach is likely to deliver the goods.
This book won the first MCA Book Prize, sponsored by the Management
Consultancies Association, announced in late March.
Details of the 1994 prize - open to British writers of management books
under the age of 45 - can be obtained from Andrea Livingstone, MCA Book
Prize Administrator, 122 Fawnbrake Avenue, London SE24 0BZ. Tel/fax 44 (0)
71-738-6701.
</TEXT>
