<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / FT Review of Business Books (6): Witty about wealth -
Quotations / Paul Taylor enjoys some cynical gems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bedside Executive
Edited by James Charlton
Robert Hale, Pounds 7.99 120 pages
A book of more than 600 quotations from business mavericks, politicians,
economists, writers and leaders of industry sounds like rather heavy going.
But even a quick peek inside the covers of The Bedside Executive is
sufficient to dispel such concerns.
This pocket-sized volume, edited by James Charlton, is packed with wise,
witty and cynical gems - mostly from North America - on topics ranging from
wealth acquisition to achieving success and doing deals.
As Mr Charlton notes in his preface, the financial and business worlds are a
particularly rich field for quotes. But while many of the wittiest come from
acknowledged humorists such as Oscar Wilde or Will Rogers, others have been
penned by unlikely wordsmiths including Henry Ford and J. Paul Getty.
Inevitably profits, money and sound business practices loom large as a
theme. Lee Iacocca, Chrysler's former chairman, once said: 'Volume times
zero isn't too healthy,' and Warren Buffet, the legendary US takeover
specialist, set out his business rules thus: 'Rule number 1: Never lose
money. Rule number 2: Never forget rule number 1'.
PT Barnum, the man who brought the circus to town, observed that: 'Money is
a terrible master, but an excellent servant,' while actor Will Rogers
advised people to 'invest in inflation. It is the only thing going up.'
Comfort for those with large overdrafts comes from the Edwardian wit, Saki
(Hector Hugh Munro), who noted: 'I'm living so far beyond my income that we
might be said to be living apart.'
Underscoring the American domination of pithy business quotes, Getty chipped
in with the classic: 'If you can count your money, you don't have a billion
dollars,' and Nelson Bunker Hunt is credited with saying: 'People who know
how much they are worth aren't usually worth that much.'
Among the observations on particular business careers are the following:
Banking. 'Banking may be a career from which no man really recovers,' said
economist John Kenneth Galbraith, while Mark Twain complained: 'A banker is
a fellow who lends you his
umbrella when the sun is shining and wants it back the minute it begins to
rain.'
Corporate finance. 'In the takeover business, if you want a friend, you buy
a dog,' according to Carl Icahn, the Wall Street financier.
Media. 'Advertising is 85 per cent confusion and 15 per cent commission,'
said American comedian Fred Allen.
Stockbroking. 'Buy when everyone is selling. And hold until everyone is
buying,' advised J. Paul Getty, while stockbroker Raymond De Voe adapted an
old axiom: 'Fools rush in where angels fear to trade.'
Economists. 'An economist is a man who states the obvious in terms of the
incomprehensible,' said publisher Alfred A. Knopf while George Bernard Shaw
quipped: 'If all economists were laid end to end, they'd never reach a
conclusion.' Herbert Hoover pleaded: 'Please find me a one-armed economist
so we will not always hear, 'On the other hand . . .' '
On the state of the economy, another US President, Harry S. Truman, said:
'It's a recession when your neighbour loses his job; its a depression when
you lose yours.'
Among the relatively sparse quotes from women, tennis star Martina
Navratilova observed that: 'Whoever said, 'it's not whether you win or lose
that counts,' probably lost,' while Margaret Thatcher chipped in with: 'If
you want anything said, ask a man. If you want anything done, ask a woman.'
Some quotations sum up their creators better than any biographical
narrative. For example Robert Maxwell, the disgraced tycoon, said: 'When I
see a belt, I cannot resist hitting below it.' Others seem strangely
prophetic such as Richard Nixon who said: 'A man is not finished when he is
defeated. He is finished when he quits.'
This is a book to dip into rather than attempt to read cover-to-cover. It is
not, nor does it pretend to be, an encyclopaedic work, although it provides
plenty of ideas for the after-dinner speaker.
Instead, as the editor notes, 'the real test of a book of quotations like
this is enjoyment, and to that end I hope this satisfies'. It does.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
