<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / FT Review of Business Books (5): A thin smile only - Humour
/ While it sounds promising, Lucy Kellaway finds a new anthology of European
jokes disappointing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCY KELLAWAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Have you heard this one? An anthology of European jokes
Europublic, Pounds 3.95 56 pages
Heaven is where the police are British, the chefs French, the mechanics
German, the lovers Italian and it is all organised by the Swiss. Hell is
where the police are German, the chefs British, the mechanics French, the
lovers Swiss and it is all organised by the Italians.
This the first joke in a book that promises to fill a gaping hole in the
market. Think of all those people who give European speeches every year, and
think of their desperation to find appropriate jokes to fill them with. This
anthology of European jokes should be an answer to their prayers.
Even for those who do not have speeches to write, the anthology sounds
promising - cracks about other nation- alities are about the funniest around
 -infinitely better than those other two hack- neyed themes: the mother-in-
law and the wife.
It is therefore both a shame and a puzzle that barely one of the jokes in
this slim volume brings more than the thinnest smile to the lips. After the
first joke, which is moderately amusing if a little aged and no longer
accurate, they fall increasingly flat.
The problem is that the book comes from the wrong stable. Europublic, the
organisation behind it, is more federally minded than Jacques Delors
himself, and is therefore not prepared to publish jokes that might offend or
ridicule any partic- ular country. This is fatal, as the whole point about
nat- ionality jokes is that they are offensive - at least to anyone touchy
enough to be offended by them. The most risque jokes in the collection
gently suggest that another nation might be just a tiny bit silly.
Funnier than some of the cracks is the commentary that goes with them. Take
this one: three prisoners of war are to be tortured to make them talk. The
French- man talks on the first day. The Englishman talks after a week. The
Italian never talks. When finally released, he is questioned about his
bravery. 'But 'ow could I talk with my hands tied behind my back?' he
replies. The joke is acceptable enough, but the commentary is hilarious.
'Think about it a bit, and you realise that, far from making fun of the
Italians, these jokes ack- nowledge that Italians are, or at least may be,
cleverer than the rest of us,' it says.
Again and again, jokes are excused by the editors on the grounds that the
victims themselves think they are funny, or because it is possible to swap
the names of the countries around to use them against a different
nationality.
There is some unexpected information to be gleaned from the book. The
Spanish, we are told, are the funniest nation of all, and have you rolling
in the aisles without even trying to be amusing. To prove it we are given
this example of their witty folk wisdom: 'If your wife tells you to throw
yourself out of the window, pray God it's a low one'. One can only reflect
that humour is a subjective thing.
Even more puzzling is the extraordinary revelation about Swedes. A Swede, a
Norwegian and a Dane are caught in a snowstorm, so the joke goes. They find
a cave to shelter in but are put off by the stench from a half-dead goat.
The Nor- wegian goes in first but comes out after five minutes asphyxiated
by the smell. Then the Dane goes in. After 10 minutes he crawls out and
expires. Finally the Swede goes in and, 15 minutes later . . . the goat
comes out.
It is not clear what this joke means. Could it be that the Swede was even
smellier than the goat? But that does not tally with one's imp- ression of
Scandinavians, and if true, would surely have been vetoed by the
collection's even-handed editors.
The anthology, though a disappointment, is not with- out its uses. Each joke
is in English, Dutch, French and German, which not only offers a painless
way of improving colloquial use of those languages, but might come in handy
for those speeches.
Take the tame joke about the Englishman who returns from a holiday in France
saying that he had no prob- lem with the language but the French did. This
might go down quite well told to a French audience by a Brit who could say
the joke in perfect French memorised from the book.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
