<DOCNO>FT942-308</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EF2DYAG6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940629
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / FT Review of Business Books (3): Leo, the tea shop's other
trade - UK Computer Business / Alan Cane recalls a preposterous episode in
Britain's postwar industrial history
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Leo: The First Business Computer
By Peter J. Bird Hasler Publishing, Pounds 15.95 272 pages
In 1947, the year before the transistor was invented, Britain's largest
catering chain decided to go into the computer business. Not satisfied with
building machines for its own use, in 1954 J. Lyons &amp; Company set up a
subsidiary, Leo Computers, to sell them to others. It remained in the
business for 17 years, eventually disposing of its interests in Leo
Computers to English Electric for Pounds 1.9m. Overall losses on the venture
were just over Pounds 100,000.
These bald facts do little justice to one of the most exciting, inventive
and, it has to be said, preposterous, episodes in postwar British industrial
history.
The Journal of the Office Management Association for 1957, quoted in Leo,
makes the argument: 'A potential computer user needs to have some confidence
in his own judgement if he is to buy his computer from a tea shop.'
Point taken: but what a tea shop] 'Joe' Lyons with its hundreds of shops and
Corner Houses, 'nippies' (waitresses) and packet tea, was a national
institution. It was tightly run with an intuitive understanding of the
importance of margins in a volume business. 'Only a farthing profit was made
on each of the 150m meals sold annually from all the teashops,' Peter Bird
notes.
His book is the first detailed account of the Leo (Lyons Electronic Office)
adventure. The machines themselves - Leo I, II and III - are now footnotes
in the history of early computers. But Leo makes an important point that has
been neglected time and again in the development of the computer industry:
successful automation depends on an understanding of what the machine can be
expected to achieve, coupled with detailed planning and documentation. If
other computer users had learned what Lyons management already knew, there
would have been fewer computer disasters over the past 40 years.
Lyons was aided here by its already meticulous office methods; but it also
employed some remarkable individuals during the Leo project, many of whom
were to go on to become mainstays of the UK computing establishment.
The project had its origin in a visit to the US in 1947 by Oliver
Standingford and 'TRT' Thompson, the senior Lyons executives responsible for
office procedures. They were impressed by early American computers and
learned that an advanced system, Edsac, already under construction at
Cambridge University, could be used as a model. 'The possible saving from
such a machine should be at least Pounds 50,000 a year,' they wrote, urging
that Lyons should build its own. The capital cost would be about Pounds
100,000.
The Lyons Board accepted the proposal in what Bird describes as 'in
retrospect, an extremely casual, but far-sighted, decision for a catering
and food manufacturing organisation to have taken during this difficult
postwar period'.
Compared with today's manufacturing costs - the price of building and
equipping a modern semiconductor fabrication plant is about Dollars 1bn  -
Lyons' initial budgetting seems comic: Pounds 140 for an oscilloscope,
Pounds 14 for benches and stools, Pounds 15 for small tools. Much of
Britain's early efforts in computing were marked by a similar grand
amateurism. The metal casing for one early computer was beaten by Mulliner
Park Ward, the Roll-Royce coach builder. Electronic consoles for Leo were at
one stage fabricated by Camper Nicholson, the yacht builder.
Ingenuity amounting at time to sheer brilliance, especially in software,
overcame the obstacles. The Leos worked and worked remarkably well. The Post
Office used them for billing until 1980 when they were replaced by ICL
mainframes, which incidentally, continued to run Leo software.
As the industry matured, the costs of staying in contention rose and Leo
Computers, which had never made money for Lyons, became too great a burden.
It was merged with English Electric and then vanished into the digital
melting pot which became ICL, now owned by Fujitsu of Japan.
Bird, director of Lyons Information Systems for 10 years, has carried out
extensive research in putting Leo together. But he is clearly more
fascinated by the technology than the personalities, which detracts from
what should read as a rattling good business tale. Characters such as John
Simmonds, Thompson and David Caminer are sketched in as stereotypes, rather
than as flesh-and-blood creatures dealing with the most complex machine the
human mind has ever created.
Bird's role as historian, however, is invaluable in placing Leo in context.
It is a welcome counter to the parade of US-authored studies which would
have you believe that nothing of note in computing happened outside North
America.
</TEXT>
<XX>
