<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Enterprise firmer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and STEVE THOMPSON.
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The performances of Enterprise Oil and Lasmo shares continued to indicate
that, as the bid moves into its closing stage, the market believes that
Lasmo will escape the clutches of Enterprise. That view was emphasised by
news that three leading stockbroking firms, Nomura, UBS and Smith New Court,
all independent of the bid battle, had advised clients to reject the
Enterprise offer.
Enterprise moved ahead 8 to 408p on turnover of 864,000 shares, while Lasmo
held steady at 141p, still well below the bid value of around 170p a share.
Turnover in Lasmo was a surprisingly high 6.3m, with a number of UK
institutions said to have moved to buy the stock on the basis that it held
long term attractions.
It was pointed out by dealers that the buying of Lasmo had been carried out
for account settlement and not for cash, indicating long term investment. It
was said that the buying of Lasmo could have represented a 'cheap' way into
Enterprise, in the event of it winning the bid battle.
Marketmakers are now bracing themselves for a possible Enterprise raid for
Lasmo shares, a move which is expected to take place from Thursday onwards,
if Enterprise is seen to be within sight of victory.
'If there is no market raid, then the chances of Enterprise winning look
pretty slim,' said one trader, who added that the market was also preparing
for a sharp slide in the Enterprise share price if it wins control of Lasmo.
The bid battle is thought to hinge on Philips &amp; Drew Fund Management, which
speaks for more than 16 per cent of Lasmo stock.
</TEXT>
