<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow hit by lower bonds and
weak Dollars
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stock markets turned sour yesterday, retreating in the face of dropping
bond prices and fresh instability in the value of the dollar, writes Frank
McGurty in New York.
However, the Dow Jones Industrial Average finished a volatile session only
15.86 lower at 3,669.64 after pulling back from a 45-point fall in the final
hours. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was down 1.23 at 446.08, but declining
issues on the Big Board outscored advances by nearly a two-to-one margin.
Volume was a moderate 268m shares.
In the secondary markets, the American SE composite was off 2.78 at 422.67,
but the Nasdaq composite held up better, dipping just 0.63 to 702.05.
At the opening, the bearish tone had little to do with the dollar. The US
currency was holding fairly steady against the yen and the D-Mark, allowing
equity investors to focus on developments elsewhere.
To the regret of the bulls, bonds caught the most attention. The Treasury
market, putting aside currency concerns, was disturbed instead by two signs
that the economy was not cooling in response to a tighter monetary policy.
In the first, the Commerce Department said sales of new homes had risen by
4.2 per cent, rebounding crisply from an April decline. In the second, the
Conference Board said consumer confidence was much higher than economists
had expected.
Inflationary fears, which had been suppressed briefly during the recent
currency crisis, resurfaced with the release of the data. With the Federal
Reserve's policy-making arm scheduled to meet next week, the timing of its
next move to lift rates again began to cast a shadow over the market's
thinking.
The effect was to drive down share prices across the board in early trading.
But the damage grew more pronounced near midday, when the dollar again began
to flirt with the Y100 level. The blue chip Dow index widened its loss, led
by stocks which were most vulnerable to a fifth Fed strike on interest
rates. Later, the market attempted to rally but there was too much ground to
retrace.
Caterpillar slipped Dollars 1 to Dollars 104 1/8 as its share price
continued to be buffeted by the implications of strike action by production
workers.
Alcoa shed Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 72 1/8 and General Motors Dollars 1 1/2
to Dollars 50 7/8 .
Financial issues, which moved in parallel with rising bond prices on Monday,
again mirrored the trend in Treasuries. JP Morgan shed Dollars 1 to Dollars
62 1/2 , First Chicago gave back Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 47 7/8 and Wells
Fargo was off Dollars 1 1/2 at Dollars 154.
Shares in Corning were marked up 6 per cent, or Dollars 1 7/8 , to Dollars
33 1/8 . The glass maker's second-quarter net income of 54 cents a share
beat the consensus forecast by 3 cents.
With technology stocks stable, the Nasdaq was able to outperform the other
leading indices. One of its best-performing issues was St Jude Medical, a
leading supplier of artificial heart valves. The stock jumped Dollars 2 1/4
to Dollars 30 3/4 on news that the company had agreed to acquire the
cardiac-pacing device businesses of Siemens for Dollars 500m.
Canada
Toronto recovered from sharp losses seen earlier in the session to end just
slightly easier after moderate trading. The TSE 300 index was off a net 6.8
points at 3,996.8. Falls led rises by 401 to 317 and volume was 52.9m
shares.
Transportation and gold stocks posted the day's largest falls of 1.97 and
1.28 per cent respectively, but the banking sector rose 1.44 per cent.
Brazil
Sao Paulo closed 5.7 per cent higher in local currency terms after investors
followed through on Monday's 8.4 per cent gain. The Bovespa index rose 1,914
to 35,635
Local investors were showing confidence over the July 1 arrival of Brazil's
new currency, the real. However, trading was thin, with foreign investors
still concerned about the prospects for Brazil's forthcoming elections.
Venezuela
Caracas fell sharply following President Rafael Caldera's announcement of
foreign exchange and price controls, with the Merinvest composite index down
8.62, or 6 per cent, to 137.08.
Volume was low at about 2.6m shares, mainly because foreign investors were
barred from trading until the new currency exchange system comes into effect
next Monday. Electricidad de Caracas fell 29.30 bolivars to 335.75 bolivars.
</TEXT>
